  "statement": "\\text{Let } R(x)=\\sec^{-1}x,\\ |x|\\ge1.\\ \\text{Find }R'(2)\\text{ and }R'(-2),\\ \\text{and state the sign relationship between them.}",
  "answer": "R'(2)=\\dfrac{1}{2\\sqrt3},\\qquad R'(-2)=\\dfrac{1}{2\\sqrt3};\\quad\\text{both are equal and POSITIVE (}R'\\text{ is even).}",
  "trap": "Students who memorise $\\dfrac{d}{dx}\\sec^{-1}x=\\dfrac{1}{x\\sqrt{x^2-1}}$ (without the absolute value) compute $R'(-2)=\\dfrac{1}{(-2)\\sqrt3}=-\\dfrac{1}{2\\sqrt3}$, a NEGATIVE value, and conclude the two are opposite in sign. But with the principal range $\\sec^{-1}:[0,\\pi]\\setminus\\{\\tfrac\\pi2\\}$, $\\sec^{-1}x$ is INCREASING on both $(-\\infty,-1]$ and $[1,\\infty)$, so its derivative must be positive everywhere. The correct formula is $\\dfrac{1}{|x|\\sqrt{x^2-1}}$, giving $R'(-2)=+\\dfrac{1}{2\\sqrt3}$.",
